	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/db/item.html?item=14887&mid=106939411217208>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/db/item.html?item=14887&mid=106939411217208>Low Down</a> <a id=fs8 href=/db/item.html?item=14887&mid=106939411217208#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Nov 21st 12:55 AM 2003</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=196206><span id= >cruelangel</span></a><br><span id=notbold>3 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>OK, here's the low down on for what essence of shadow is used.&nbsp;&nbsp;It takes two essence of shadow, as well as an elven blood and a neriak nectar to make a temper for dark elf smithing.  Aside from that, it's only useful to sell (and man, do people love to gouge the dark elves).  It's super hard to come by, as you can see from the other posts, and it's used in <b>every</b> piece of Dark Elven armor, as well as the few weapons we can make.  So if you come across some, and are already loaded, do the Dark Elven society a favor, and sell it at a reasonable price, say 40 pp or less.  100 pp per essence is unreal, that means 200 pp on just the temper, plus the cost of adamantite (which isn't cheap either), hammers, patterns, enchanted metals, imbued stones (just try to find a high level Dark Elf cleric) and other random ingredients.</p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
